                       <bindingDesc>
                         <binding contemporary="true Ethiopian" xml:id="binding">
                             <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                               The manuscript is bound in <material key="wood">wooden</material> boards and covered with <material key="leather"/> on the spine.
                             </decoNote>
                             <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                               The boards are cut to the same size as the bookblock and have shallow external bevels. The grain runs vertically.
                               The external surface of the boards is polished, while the inner surface exhibits signs of the working tool.
                             </decoNote>
                             <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                             <decoNote xml:id="b4">
                               The sewing is a chainstitch on four sewing stations, broken and repaired with a different kind of thread. Both threads are Z-plied.
                              </decoNote>
                             <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="Spine">
                               The small holes close to the head and tail of the quires probably indicate that quire tackets were originally present.
                               A sheet of parchment is folded around and sewn with the bookblock. <locus target="#1"/> and <locus target="#96"/> are the extensions
                               of this sort of spine lining. A piece of brown leather has been sewn over it as an additional protection.
                             </decoNote>
                             <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SlipCase">
                               The original leather slip case is preserved. It is a one-piece, double-walled satchel where the back panel overlaps over the front.
                               The satchel is equipped with long flaps extending from the side panels and a main rounded flap extending from the back to the front
                               panel to cover the opening of the book compartment.
                               The hanging strap is formed by two strips of leather whose ends are overlapped and stitched together. The strap passes through two flaps
                               extending from the bottom panel and slides under a leather belt wrapped around all the sides that also keeps the main flap closed.
                             </decoNote>
                         </binding>
